  note = {CORE ARGUMENT: Ethnographic study of nearly 80 Airbnb hosts, Uber drivers, TaskRabbit assistants, and Kitchensurfing chefs examines contradictions between gig economy promises and lived experiences. Identifies three worker types: Success Stories (created desired life), Strugglers (can't make ends meet), and Strivers (stable jobs using gig for extra cash). Exposes gig economy as millennial's version of minimum-wage precarious work, examining how lofty promises contrast with reality of rolling back workplace protections. Draws on eight months fieldwork as Deliveroo rider participating in organizing. RELEVANCE: Important typology showing variation in platform worker experiences and outcomes. Not all platform workers equally disadvantaged - experiences mediated by existing resources and goals. Success/Struggler/Striver framework reveals how inequality shapes gig economy participation and consequences. Demonstrates gig economy reproduces and intensifies existing stratification. Essential for understanding heterogeneous impacts of platform work. Challenges both optimistic and uniformly pessimistic narratives. POSITION: Economic sociology (ethnography, worker typology, sharing economy).},
